You know, swipe animations

00:27:12.626 --> 00:27:14.006 A:middle
lining right up with those swipe

00:27:14.046 --> 00:27:14.596 A:middle
gestures.

00:27:15.416 --> 00:27:17.036 A:middle
And the best apps appear

00:27:17.036 --> 00:27:18.916 A:middle
visually perfect, and that is

00:27:18.976 --> 00:27:20.346 A:middle
just totally remarkable.

00:27:20.896 --> 00:27:22.506 A:middle
And she also mentioned games.

00:27:23.216 --> 00:27:25.676 A:middle
Games should absolutely aspire

00:27:25.776 --> 00:27:26.406 A:middle
to be stunning.

00:27:27.226 --> 00:27:29.706 A:middle
Games are a perfect escape from

00:27:29.706 --> 00:27:32.316 A:middle
this world into a different one.

00:27:32.896 --> 00:27:34.656 A:middle
And they accomplish this through

00:27:34.656 --> 00:27:36.586 A:middle
stunning, immersive visuals.

00:27:37.806 --> 00:27:39.466 A:middle
I mean, I love TV and movies,

00:27:39.546 --> 00:27:41.056 A:middle
but that's a really passive

00:27:41.056 --> 00:27:41.626 A:middle
escape.

00:27:42.186 --> 00:27:43.416 A:middle
In games, well, they're an

00:27:43.416 --> 00:27:44.986 A:middle
active one, and that's why I

00:27:45.046 --> 00:27:45.586 A:middle
love them.

00:27:46.396 --> 00:27:48.036 A:middle
But there is one essential thing

00:27:48.386 --> 00:27:49.896 A:middle
that all games must do.

00:27:50.966 --> 00:27:53.386 A:middle
They must teach you, the player,

00:27:53.626 --> 00:27:53.926 A:middle
the rules.

00:27:53.926 --> 00:27:56.086 A:middle
And this is really a first

00:27:56.086 --> 00:27:57.536 A:middle
impression that people have of a

00:27:57.536 --> 00:27:59.996 A:middle
lot of games, so it makes me

00:27:59.996 --> 00:28:02.426 A:middle
really sad when games make a bad

00:27:59.996 --> 00:28:02.426 A:middle
really sad when games make a bad

00:28:02.486 --> 00:28:04.746 A:middle
first impression because when

00:28:04.746 --> 00:28:06.946 A:middle
I'm trying to learn, well, the

00:28:06.946 --> 00:28:08.576 A:middle
rules feel slapped together,

00:28:09.066 --> 00:28:11.076 A:middle
added on last minute, or it just

00:28:11.076 --> 00:28:12.316 A:middle
doesn't feel a part of the

00:28:12.316 --> 00:28:13.086 A:middle
game's world.

00:28:13.086 --> 00:28:16.706 A:middle
So I decided to ask Sam, who's

00:28:16.706 --> 00:28:18.136 A:middle
working on an upcoming game

00:28:18.136 --> 00:28:20.416 A:middle
called Where Cards Fall, "How do

00:28:20.416 --> 00:28:22.036 A:middle
you learn the rules of the game

00:28:22.346 --> 00:28:24.116 A:middle
all while staying in the game's

00:28:24.116 --> 00:28:24.436 A:middle
world?"

00:28:24.926 --> 00:28:27.326 A:middle
&gt;&gt; With games in particular,

00:28:27.326 --> 00:28:29.066 A:middle
there's a real joy that can come

00:28:29.166 --> 00:28:31.196 A:middle
from discovering what they can

00:28:31.196 --> 00:28:33.126 A:middle
do and learning for yourself.

00:28:33.186 --> 00:28:34.916 A:middle
People tend to remember things

00:28:35.046 --> 00:28:37.206 A:middle
the best when they experience

00:28:37.206 --> 00:28:38.636 A:middle
them themselves, when they learn

00:28:38.826 --> 00:28:40.496 A:middle
them through some sort of active

00:28:40.496 --> 00:28:41.526 A:middle
discovery.

00:28:41.526 --> 00:28:43.996 A:middle
So if we give them too much at

00:28:43.996 --> 00:28:45.556 A:middle
the beginning, we're robbing

00:28:45.556 --> 00:28:47.296 A:middle
them of that chance to reward

00:28:47.296 --> 00:28:48.386 A:middle
their own curiosity.

00:28:48.696 --> 00:28:49.926 A:middle
So we always want to make sure

00:28:49.986 --> 00:28:51.446 A:middle
that they stay curious, that

00:28:51.446 --> 00:28:52.586 A:middle
they stay interested throughout

00:28:52.586 --> 00:28:54.976 A:middle
the entire experience, and that

00:28:55.076 --> 00:28:56.046 A:middle
they have a lot of different

00:28:56.046 --> 00:28:57.176 A:middle
moments where they can be

00:28:57.176 --> 00:28:58.566 A:middle
rewarded for trying something.

00:28:58.566 --> 00:29:00.086 A:middle
And when they try something and

00:28:58.566 --> 00:29:00.086 A:middle
And when they try something and

00:29:00.086 --> 00:29:01.546 A:middle
they discover something for the

00:29:01.546 --> 00:29:03.126 A:middle
first time, they definitely

00:29:03.126 --> 00:29:03.806 A:middle
won't forget it.

00:29:03.806 --> 00:29:04.886 A:middle
But if we throw up like a

00:29:04.886 --> 00:29:06.746 A:middle
tooltip or some way of just

00:29:06.746 --> 00:29:08.676 A:middle
making sure that we as the game

00:29:08.676 --> 00:29:09.746 A:middle
designers are comfortable

00:29:09.746 --> 00:29:10.426 A:middle
knowing that they know

00:29:10.426 --> 00:29:12.206 A:middle
something, there's a pretty good

00:29:12.206 --> 00:29:13.066 A:middle
chance that they'll forget it

00:29:13.066 --> 00:29:14.676 A:middle
later on since they didn't go

00:29:14.676 --> 00:29:15.676 A:middle
through the process of learning

00:29:15.676 --> 00:29:15.976 A:middle
it themselves.

00:29:19.976 --> 00:29:21.826 A:middle
So when I go into a game for the

00:29:21.916 --> 00:29:24.476 A:middle
first time, I want to learn how

00:29:24.476 --> 00:29:26.776 A:middle
to navigate the world, if it

00:29:26.776 --> 00:29:29.296 A:middle
takes place in a world, as

00:29:29.296 --> 00:29:30.496 A:middle
quickly as possible or just how

00:29:30.496 --> 00:29:31.656 A:middle
to understand the rules of the

00:29:31.656 --> 00:29:33.956 A:middle
game as quickly as possible, but

00:29:34.146 --> 00:29:35.986 A:middle
not so quickly that I'm kind of

00:29:35.986 --> 00:29:37.266 A:middle
robbed of my curiosity to

00:29:37.266 --> 00:29:38.446 A:middle
explore them a little bit

00:29:38.526 --> 00:29:38.896 A:middle
further.

00:29:39.446 --> 00:29:42.546 A:middle
So I tend to get a sense for

00:29:42.626 --> 00:29:44.646 A:middle
what the game is, and if the

00:29:44.646 --> 00:29:46.466 A:middle
game continues to surprise me,

00:29:46.796 --> 00:29:48.716 A:middle
I'll make it through to the

00:29:48.716 --> 00:29:50.016 A:middle
finish line.

00:29:51.286 --> 00:29:53.376 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Wow, that was learning the

00:29:53.376 --> 00:29:55.436 A:middle
rules in Where Cards Fall, and

00:29:55.576 --> 00:29:57.156 A:middle
that definitely feels a part of

00:29:57.156 --> 00:29:59.626 A:middle
the game's world, and I think

00:29:59.626 --> 00:30:01.136 A:middle
everyone can learn from what Sam

00:29:59.626 --> 00:30:01.136 A:middle
everyone can learn from what Sam

00:30:01.176 --> 00:30:03.266 A:middle
said about active discovery.

00:30:03.706 --> 00:30:05.256 A:middle
And this is not just for games.

00:30:05.766 --> 00:30:07.696 A:middle
Active discovery is so much

00:30:07.736 --> 00:30:09.696 A:middle
better than reading tooltips or

00:30:09.696 --> 00:30:12.106 A:middle
chasing a pointing arrow, and to

00:30:12.196 --> 00:30:14.826 A:middle
Sam's point, being told isn't as

00:30:14.826 --> 00:30:17.206 A:middle
much fun or, frankly, effective

00:30:17.436 --> 00:30:19.016 A:middle
as discovering something for

00:30:19.016 --> 00:30:19.516 A:middle
yourself.

00:30:20.686 --> 00:30:22.346 A:middle
It's kind of like being told

00:30:22.346 --> 00:30:24.876 A:middle
about a vacation versus being on

00:30:24.876 --> 00:30:25.906 A:middle
that vacation yourself.

00:30:26.706 --> 00:30:28.246 A:middle
It's way more fun, and you're

00:30:28.246 --> 00:30:29.666 A:middle
just going to remember it better

00:30:29.666 --> 00:30:31.416 A:middle
if you actually go through that

00:30:31.416 --> 00:30:32.116 A:middle
experience.

00:30:33.536 --> 00:30:35.106 A:middle
So whether you're creating an

00:30:35.106 --> 00:30:38.176 A:middle
app or a game, aspire to be

00:30:38.176 --> 00:30:38.776 A:middle
stunning.

00:30:39.216 --> 00:30:41.136 A:middle
Create beautiful experiences,

00:30:41.646 --> 00:30:43.696 A:middle
polish your visual design so it

00:30:43.696 --> 00:30:45.856 A:middle
looks and feels just a part of

00:30:45.856 --> 00:30:47.436 A:middle
your app or game's world.

00:30:47.956 --> 00:30:49.816 A:middle
Okay, timeless.

00:30:51.236 --> 00:30:54.156 A:middle
This has been on my mind since

00:30:54.206 --> 00:30:55.586 A:middle
talking with Hugo, a sound

00:30:55.586 --> 00:30:56.036 A:middle
designer.

00:30:56.716 --> 00:30:59.136 A:middle
Most of you will recognize this.

00:31:00.516 --> 00:31:10.196 A:middle
[ Ringtone ]

00:31:10.696 --> 00:31:11.876 A:middle
I'm always looking for where

00:31:11.876 --> 00:31:13.296 A:middle
that phone is.

00:31:13.496 --> 00:31:14.926 A:middle
But what reminded me of this

00:31:14.966 --> 00:31:17.726 A:middle
ringtone was this part of the

00:31:17.726 --> 00:31:18.376 A:middle
interview.

00:31:18.976 --> 00:31:23.406 A:middle
&gt;&gt; If we create a ringtone for

00:31:24.076 --> 00:31:27.126 A:middle
the new iPhone, then we don't

00:31:27.126 --> 00:31:28.916 A:middle
want it to sound dated after a

00:31:28.916 --> 00:31:29.776 A:middle
year, of course.

00:31:29.776 --> 00:31:31.766 A:middle
It should still be a great

00:31:32.356 --> 00:31:34.606 A:middle
ringtone after 5 years, and

00:31:34.606 --> 00:31:35.946 A:middle
maybe people will still remember

00:31:35.946 --> 00:31:36.936 A:middle
it after 10 years.

00:31:37.476 --> 00:31:41.286 A:middle
&gt;&gt; It was actually this section

00:31:41.696 --> 00:31:43.456 A:middle
of the quote that really made me

00:31:43.576 --> 00:31:45.116 A:middle
think of timelessness.

00:31:46.316 --> 00:31:47.486 A:middle
You know, it makes sense for a

00:31:47.486 --> 00:31:49.126 A:middle
ringtone not to want to sound

00:31:49.126 --> 00:31:51.706 A:middle
dated, but this could also apply

00:31:51.706 --> 00:31:53.246 A:middle
to your visual and interaction

00:31:53.246 --> 00:31:54.256 A:middle
design too.

00:31:55.376 --> 00:31:57.726 A:middle
Hugo used this word "durability"

00:31:57.986 --> 00:32:00.006 A:middle
to describe quality during our

00:31:57.986 --> 00:32:00.006 A:middle
to describe quality during our

00:32:00.006 --> 00:32:01.686 A:middle
interview, and I think that's

00:32:01.846 --> 00:32:02.476 A:middle
really great.

00:32:03.256 --> 00:32:04.996 A:middle
If we all aspire to create

00:32:04.996 --> 00:32:06.246 A:middle
designs that are just a little

00:32:06.246 --> 00:32:08.556 A:middle
bit longer lasting, it not only

00:32:08.556 --> 00:32:10.036 A:middle
would save us time and effort

00:32:10.036 --> 00:32:12.596 A:middle
now, but it would put us into

00:32:12.596 --> 00:32:14.536 A:middle
the right mindset to provide

00:32:14.586 --> 00:32:15.806 A:middle
something that we create with

00:32:15.806 --> 00:32:20.916 A:middle
the opportunity to be timeless.

00:32:21.036 --> 00:32:23.466 A:middle
This final aspiration really had

00:32:23.466 --> 00:32:25.536 A:middle
an impact on me, and it came

00:32:25.536 --> 00:32:27.166 A:middle
from my colleague Doug when I

00:32:27.166 --> 00:32:29.376 A:middle
asked him, "What makes great app

00:32:29.506 --> 00:32:29.976 A:middle
experiences?"

00:32:32.216 --> 00:32:34.126 A:middle
&gt;&gt; When I think of, like, great

00:32:34.246 --> 00:32:36.366 A:middle
app experiences and things that

00:32:36.446 --> 00:32:38.466 A:middle
kind of provide something unique

00:32:38.466 --> 00:32:40.676 A:middle
and valuable to users, I think a

00:32:40.676 --> 00:32:43.556 A:middle
lot of it is the substantial

00:32:43.556 --> 00:32:45.496 A:middle
kind of positive effect that it

00:32:45.496 --> 00:32:47.546 A:middle
has on the user's life.

00:32:48.996 --> 00:32:51.066 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Doug, you nailed it.

00:32:51.526 --> 00:32:53.486 A:middle
Yes, absolutely, apps should

00:32:53.486 --> 00:32:54.956 A:middle
provide something unique and

00:32:54.956 --> 00:32:57.366 A:middle
valuable, but, actually, it was

00:32:57.366 --> 00:32:58.946 A:middle
this part, the positive effect,

00:32:59.216 --> 00:33:00.796 A:middle
that really resonated with me.

00:32:59.216 --> 00:33:00.796 A:middle
that really resonated with me.

00:33:01.806 --> 00:33:03.966 A:middle
It made me reassess the apps and

00:33:03.966 --> 00:33:04.916 A:middle
games on my phone.

00:33:05.476 --> 00:33:06.726 A:middle
After this interview, I

00:33:06.726 --> 00:33:08.786 A:middle
literally scrolled through all

00:33:08.786 --> 00:33:10.876 A:middle
of my apps, and I thought, which

00:33:10.876 --> 00:33:13.136 A:middle
ones have a positive effect on

00:33:13.226 --> 00:33:14.286 A:middle
my life?

00:33:14.916 --> 00:33:17.036 A:middle
You know, wouldn't it be great

00:33:17.546 --> 00:33:19.346 A:middle
if life just had a little more

00:33:19.476 --> 00:33:20.226 A:middle
positivity?

00:33:21.616 --> 00:33:24.396 A:middle
So next time you design, strive

00:33:24.396 --> 00:33:26.676 A:middle
for simplicity because real life

00:33:26.876 --> 00:33:28.086 A:middle
if where we need to be spending

00:33:28.086 --> 00:33:28.736 A:middle
our energy.

00:33:29.936 --> 00:33:32.826 A:middle
Aspire to be stunning because we

00:33:32.826 --> 00:33:34.896 A:middle
all need a break from chaos, and

00:33:34.896 --> 00:33:36.676 A:middle
it's really nice to escape and

00:33:36.676 --> 00:33:38.056 A:middle
experience something beautiful.

00:33:38.566 --> 00:33:41.016 A:middle
Design to be timeless.

00:33:41.776 --> 00:33:43.126 A:middle
Think about how your designs can

00:33:43.126 --> 00:33:45.586 A:middle
be good now but also years from

00:33:45.586 --> 00:33:47.826 A:middle
now because we could all design

00:33:47.866 --> 00:33:49.666 A:middle
to be a little less trendy and

00:33:49.666 --> 00:33:51.006 A:middle
definitely more durable.

00:33:51.606 --> 00:33:54.806 A:middle
And finally, think about how you

00:33:54.806 --> 00:33:56.456 A:middle
could have a positive impact on

00:33:56.456 --> 00:33:56.916 A:middle
people's lives.

00:33:58.196 --> 00:33:59.456 A:middle
And, you know, this can manifest

00:33:59.496 --> 00:34:01.216 A:middle
itself in really different ways

00:33:59.496 --> 00:34:01.216 A:middle
itself in really different ways

00:34:01.216 --> 00:34:02.896 A:middle
depending on your app.

00:34:02.896 --> 00:34:04.166 A:middle
It could be maybe that

00:34:04.166 --> 00:34:05.586 A:middle
positivity is being really

00:34:05.586 --> 00:34:07.566 A:middle
accurate, or maybe it's just

00:34:07.566 --> 00:34:08.706 A:middle
being super entertaining.

00:34:09.616 --> 00:34:10.806 A:middle
Maybe it's just making someone's

00:34:10.806 --> 00:34:13.216 A:middle
life or day feel a little bit

00:34:13.216 --> 00:34:13.656 A:middle
easier.

00:34:13.656 --> 00:34:16.466 A:middle
I hope that you found some of

00:34:16.466 --> 00:34:17.396 A:middle
these thoughts to be as

00:34:17.396 --> 00:34:18.706 A:middle
inspiring as I did.

00:34:20.255 --> 00:34:21.186 A:middle
I'm sure you're thinking now,

00:34:21.186 --> 00:34:22.735 A:middle
though, well, sure, this has

00:34:22.735 --> 00:34:24.545 A:middle
been mildly inspiring and

00:34:24.636 --> 00:34:26.706 A:middle
somewhat educational, but what

00:34:26.706 --> 00:34:27.585 A:middle
can I do?

00:34:27.585 --> 00:34:29.196 A:middle
What can I actually take away

00:34:29.196 --> 00:34:30.476 A:middle
and apply to my work?

00:34:30.476 --> 00:34:33.186 A:middle
Well, I wanted to know that too.

00:34:33.906 --> 00:34:35.326 A:middle
After talking with so many

00:34:35.326 --> 00:34:36.536 A:middle
different people from different

00:34:36.536 --> 00:34:38.545 A:middle
backgrounds, I wanted to know

00:34:38.646 --> 00:34:40.426 A:middle
what they learned -- what they

00:34:40.426 --> 00:34:42.045 A:middle
learned on the job through their

00:34:42.045 --> 00:34:43.036 A:middle
experiences.

00:34:43.576 --> 00:34:44.476 A:middle
So through a series of

00:34:44.476 --> 00:34:46.456 A:middle
questions, I uncovered a few

00:34:46.606 --> 00:34:48.616 A:middle
tips and techniques that these

00:34:48.616 --> 00:34:50.755 A:middle
designers use regularly when

00:34:50.755 --> 00:34:51.306 A:middle
designing.

00:34:52.005 --> 00:34:53.295 A:middle
And something important to

00:34:53.295 --> 00:34:54.786 A:middle
mention about design before we

00:34:54.786 --> 00:34:58.726 A:middle
get started is, yes, design is

00:34:58.756 --> 00:35:01.306 A:middle
hard because nobody sets out to

00:34:58.756 --> 00:35:01.306 A:middle
hard because nobody sets out to

00:35:01.306 --> 00:35:02.196 A:middle
create a bad app.

00:35:02.966 --> 00:35:04.866 A:middle
Making great designs is what we

00:35:04.946 --> 00:35:07.796 A:middle
all strive for, but let's be

00:35:07.796 --> 00:35:08.206 A:middle
honest.

00:35:08.816 --> 00:35:11.136 A:middle
We don't always achieve it, and

00:35:11.136 --> 00:35:12.956 A:middle
that's okay because we keep

00:35:12.956 --> 00:35:15.296 A:middle
trying and we learn a lot along

00:35:15.296 --> 00:35:15.516 A:middle
the way.

00:35:16.796 --> 00:35:19.756 A:middle
Okay, let's go ahead and hear

00:35:19.756 --> 00:35:21.546 A:middle
this first technique, and it

00:35:21.546 --> 00:35:22.576 A:middle
really surprised me.

00:35:22.976 --> 00:35:24.196 A:middle
It came up when I was talking

00:35:24.286 --> 00:35:25.166 A:middle
with Loic [phonetic], a type

00:35:25.216 --> 00:35:27.586 A:middle
designer, and I asked him, "What

00:35:27.586 --> 00:35:29.986 A:middle
helps you with your work?"

00:35:30.776 --> 00:35:32.056 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So in the case of type

00:35:32.056 --> 00:35:33.236 A:middle
design, for instance, we've

00:35:33.796 --> 00:35:35.656 A:middle
developed all kinds of little

00:35:35.826 --> 00:35:36.906 A:middle
drawing tricks.

00:35:36.906 --> 00:35:38.296 A:middle
In type design especially,

00:35:38.886 --> 00:35:41.036 A:middle
subjectiveness I feel can

00:35:41.036 --> 00:35:42.496 A:middle
[inaudible] even more than in

00:35:42.496 --> 00:35:44.106 A:middle
other aspects of design because

00:35:44.106 --> 00:35:46.706 A:middle
we go to the depth of how the

00:35:46.706 --> 00:35:48.196 A:middle
particular curve of, on the

00:35:48.196 --> 00:35:50.366 A:middle
shoulder of a lowercase m is,

00:35:50.366 --> 00:35:50.916 A:middle
for instance.

00:35:50.916 --> 00:35:52.566 A:middle
And we can have a 10-minute

00:35:52.566 --> 00:35:54.906 A:middle
discussion only on that.

00:35:55.046 --> 00:35:56.496 A:middle
But the difficult part is

00:35:56.596 --> 00:35:59.596 A:middle
describing what you see in words

00:35:59.596 --> 00:36:01.286 A:middle
that the other person is going

00:35:59.596 --> 00:36:01.286 A:middle
that the other person is going

00:36:01.286 --> 00:36:03.006 A:middle
to understand the way you mean

00:36:03.006 --> 00:36:05.036 A:middle
it, and that's very difficult

00:36:05.036 --> 00:36:06.106 A:middle
when you're talking about shape.

00:36:06.696 --> 00:36:08.976 A:middle
But one way we started doing

00:36:08.976 --> 00:36:10.266 A:middle
that with some of my colleagues

00:36:10.266 --> 00:36:12.386 A:middle
was basically redrawing the

00:36:12.386 --> 00:36:14.076 A:middle
shape we're looking at with

00:36:14.076 --> 00:36:16.566 A:middle
exaggerated features, where we

00:36:16.566 --> 00:36:18.406 A:middle
basically kind of make a

00:36:18.406 --> 00:36:19.676 A:middle
caricature of what we are

00:36:19.676 --> 00:36:20.156 A:middle
seeing.

00:36:20.886 --> 00:36:22.916 A:middle
So if I'm pushing what I'm

00:36:22.916 --> 00:36:25.366 A:middle
seeing to the extreme of why I

00:36:25.476 --> 00:36:27.966 A:middle
find it ugly or uncomfortable,

00:36:28.256 --> 00:36:30.456 A:middle
it's because it feels like that

00:36:30.456 --> 00:36:30.696 A:middle
to me.

00:36:31.536 --> 00:36:32.616 A:middle
And through that drawing,

00:36:32.616 --> 00:36:33.876 A:middle
usually the other people can

00:36:33.876 --> 00:36:36.076 A:middle
start seeing that much more

00:36:36.076 --> 00:36:38.506 A:middle
toned down but existing feature

00:36:38.506 --> 00:36:40.116 A:middle
of the design that they weren't

00:36:40.116 --> 00:36:41.616 A:middle
necessarily perceiving before

00:36:41.616 --> 00:36:42.906 A:middle
because that's not what they

00:36:42.906 --> 00:36:44.386 A:middle
were looking at.

00:36:44.486 --> 00:36:46.086 A:middle
So it is about trying to make

00:36:46.086 --> 00:36:48.466 A:middle
people see the world through

00:36:48.526 --> 00:36:50.416 A:middle
your eyes and the other way

00:36:50.476 --> 00:36:52.206 A:middle
around, like gaining the ability

00:36:52.206 --> 00:36:53.206 A:middle
to see the world through their

00:36:53.206 --> 00:36:55.686 A:middle
eyes, so that you can then find

00:36:55.686 --> 00:36:56.926 A:middle
that third place that is

00:36:56.926 --> 00:37:00.906 A:middle
actually the joint gaze that you

00:36:56.926 --> 00:37:00.906 A:middle
actually the joint gaze that you

00:37:00.906 --> 00:37:01.696 A:middle
have on the world.

00:37:02.086 --> 00:37:04.916 A:middle
And that's the, that I think to

00:37:04.916 --> 00:37:07.016 A:middle
me is the key of a successful

00:37:07.016 --> 00:37:08.756 A:middle
collaboration in design is

00:37:08.756 --> 00:37:13.656 A:middle
finding that place.

00:37:13.886 --> 00:37:15.946 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Wow. Before we even dig into

00:37:15.946 --> 00:37:17.826 A:middle
this technique, have you thought

00:37:17.896 --> 00:37:19.076 A:middle
about type design?

00:37:19.436 --> 00:37:20.896 A:middle
I mean, every single letter that

00:37:20.956 --> 00:37:22.956 A:middle
you text, and email, and that

00:37:22.956 --> 00:37:24.696 A:middle
you read, that's been designed,

00:37:25.546 --> 00:37:27.666 A:middle
and type designers care so much

00:37:27.706 --> 00:37:29.336 A:middle
about detail that they've

00:37:29.336 --> 00:37:31.176 A:middle
invented ways to communicate

00:37:31.176 --> 00:37:33.256 A:middle
about shape when there are no

00:37:33.256 --> 00:37:33.696 A:middle
words.

00:37:34.586 --> 00:37:35.736 A:middle
That's just so cool.

00:37:36.776 --> 00:37:38.446 A:middle
So to Loic's point, when you're

00:37:38.446 --> 00:37:40.226 A:middle
designing for others, it's

00:37:40.366 --> 00:37:42.016 A:middle
really necessary to see the

00:37:42.016 --> 00:37:44.046 A:middle
world through their eyes, and

00:37:44.126 --> 00:37:45.546 A:middle
this technique helps achieve

00:37:46.596 --> 00:37:46.686 A:middle
that.

00:37:46.846 --> 00:37:50.256 A:middle
So draw caricatures and ask

00:37:50.256 --> 00:37:51.456 A:middle
others to do the same.

00:37:52.196 --> 00:37:53.416 A:middle
It's really the importance of

00:37:53.416 --> 00:37:54.636 A:middle
putting yourself in others'

00:37:54.636 --> 00:37:56.276 A:middle
shoes because you can better

00:37:56.276 --> 00:37:57.496 A:middle
understand their world.

00:37:58.126 --> 00:37:59.686 A:middle
And this is a great tool for

00:37:59.686 --> 00:38:01.786 A:middle
communication if words are not

00:37:59.686 --> 00:38:01.786 A:middle
communication if words are not

00:38:01.866 --> 00:38:03.306 A:middle
doing it, and it'll help you

00:38:03.306 --> 00:38:04.546 A:middle
understand what others are

00:38:04.546 --> 00:38:04.986 A:middle
seeing.

00:38:05.526 --> 00:38:08.416 A:middle
This next technique is going to

00:38:08.416 --> 00:38:10.236 A:middle
be unveiled through a story.

00:38:10.916 --> 00:38:13.236 A:middle
Actually, even better, a first

00:38:13.446 --> 00:38:14.426 A:middle
job story.

00:38:15.176 --> 00:38:17.226 A:middle
Because you learn a lot on your

00:38:17.226 --> 00:38:19.286 A:middle
first job, and they have a huge

00:38:19.286 --> 00:38:19.616 A:middle
impact.

00:38:20.716 --> 00:38:22.356 A:middle
So I asked my colleague Doug

00:38:22.496 --> 00:38:24.106 A:middle
what he learned at his first

00:38:24.286 --> 00:38:24.946 A:middle
design job.

00:38:25.526 --> 00:38:30.296 A:middle
&gt;&gt; One of the real kind of ahas

00:38:30.296 --> 00:38:33.406 A:middle
for me was a question that I got

00:38:33.406 --> 00:38:35.196 A:middle
at the Tech Museum from the Head

00:38:35.196 --> 00:38:37.546 A:middle
of Design that was essentially,

00:38:37.936 --> 00:38:39.056 A:middle
why is this good?

00:38:39.566 --> 00:38:41.166 A:middle
Why is this thing that you just

00:38:41.166 --> 00:38:42.376 A:middle
gave me good?

00:38:42.816 --> 00:38:45.486 A:middle
And, you know, my initial

00:38:45.486 --> 00:38:47.276 A:middle
reaction was, well, because I

00:38:47.346 --> 00:38:49.366 A:middle
think this will be easy for

00:38:49.366 --> 00:38:50.316 A:middle
people to do.

00:38:50.546 --> 00:38:53.326 A:middle
And, you know, he responded,

00:38:53.326 --> 00:38:54.406 A:middle
like, well, how do you know

00:38:54.406 --> 00:38:54.576 A:middle
that?

00:38:54.796 --> 00:38:55.966 A:middle
How do you know that this is

00:38:55.966 --> 00:38:57.666 A:middle
going to be easier than the way

00:38:57.666 --> 00:38:58.486 A:middle
that we do it now?

00:38:58.896 --> 00:39:01.946 A:middle
And I kind of realized that I

00:38:58.896 --> 00:39:01.946 A:middle
And I kind of realized that I

00:39:01.946 --> 00:39:03.446 A:middle
didn't know the answer to that.

00:39:03.446 --> 00:39:05.056 A:middle
And then, I realized what he was

00:39:05.056 --> 00:39:07.716 A:middle
really asking is, should we put

00:39:07.716 --> 00:39:10.046 A:middle
all of this energy into making

00:39:10.046 --> 00:39:11.816 A:middle
the changes that you're

00:39:11.816 --> 00:39:12.756 A:middle
suggesting?

00:39:13.236 --> 00:39:14.546 A:middle
How can we be sure that that's

00:39:14.546 --> 00:39:15.696 A:middle
the right thing to do?

00:39:15.926 --> 00:39:18.756 A:middle
And to answer that question, I

00:39:19.416 --> 00:39:21.306 A:middle
opened up -- it might have been

00:39:21.306 --> 00:39:23.656 A:middle
Microsoft Paint [laughs] -- and

00:39:23.656 --> 00:39:27.136 A:middle
I drew a picture, and I took it

00:39:27.136 --> 00:39:29.706 A:middle
out onto the museum floor, and

00:39:29.806 --> 00:39:32.756 A:middle
basically asked visitors to give

00:39:32.756 --> 00:39:35.176 A:middle
me their impression of what they

00:39:35.376 --> 00:39:37.446 A:middle
thought they should do based on

00:39:37.706 --> 00:39:39.176 A:middle
kind of how I had arranged

00:39:39.176 --> 00:39:40.136 A:middle
things on the screen.

00:39:41.606 --> 00:39:42.816 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So what Doug was talking

00:39:42.816 --> 00:39:44.146 A:middle
about here, and he went on to

00:39:44.226 --> 00:39:46.596 A:middle
explain, that it was this method

00:39:46.596 --> 00:39:48.736 A:middle
of prototyping that helped him

00:39:48.736 --> 00:39:50.026 A:middle
answer that question from his

00:39:50.076 --> 00:39:50.376 A:middle
boss.

00:39:51.206 --> 00:39:53.156 A:middle
Why should we put energy into

00:39:53.156 --> 00:39:53.786 A:middle
your idea?

00:39:54.736 --> 00:39:56.156 A:middle
So what Doug learned at his

00:39:56.276 --> 00:39:58.196 A:middle
first design job was that he

00:39:58.226 --> 00:40:00.096 A:middle
could not assume that his

00:39:58.226 --> 00:40:00.096 A:middle
could not assume that his

00:40:00.096 --> 00:40:01.236 A:middle
designs were going to work.

00:40:01.236 --> 00:40:03.476 A:middle
And this actually also came up

00:40:03.476 --> 00:40:05.106 A:middle
in my conversation with Gary.

00:40:06.606 --> 00:40:07.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; It wasn't just designed on

00:40:07.666 --> 00:40:10.306 A:middle
paper, implemented in code, and

00:40:10.306 --> 00:40:13.046 A:middle
sort of assumed that that was

00:40:13.046 --> 00:40:13.336 A:middle
going to work.

00:40:13.336 --> 00:40:15.906 A:middle
You can't just assume from your

00:40:15.906 --> 00:40:18.266 A:middle
own experience and through

00:40:18.476 --> 00:40:19.756 A:middle
chatting that something's going

00:40:19.756 --> 00:40:20.006 A:middle
to work.

00:40:20.006 --> 00:40:20.766 A:middle
You've really got to go out and

00:40:20.766 --> 00:40:20.956 A:middle
try it.

00:40:23.106 --> 00:40:24.236 A:middle
&gt;&gt; And I think this is the part

00:40:24.236 --> 00:40:25.886 A:middle
that's really important not to

00:40:25.886 --> 00:40:26.326 A:middle
overlook.

00:40:27.516 --> 00:40:28.616 A:middle
You know, in this case, we are

00:40:28.616 --> 00:40:30.296 A:middle
talking about trying designs in

00:40:30.296 --> 00:40:32.906 A:middle
context out in the real world to

00:40:32.906 --> 00:40:35.186 A:middle
vet solutions to problems, and

00:40:35.186 --> 00:40:36.706 A:middle
trying solutions is something

00:40:36.706 --> 00:40:37.956 A:middle
that Sam mentioned too.

00:40:39.486 --> 00:40:42.196 A:middle
&gt;&gt; One of our ethos's is to

00:40:42.196 --> 00:40:43.086 A:middle
solve a problem.

00:40:43.286 --> 00:40:45.196 A:middle
Put it in front of players and

00:40:45.306 --> 00:40:46.416 A:middle
see how they react.

00:40:46.486 --> 00:40:47.316 A:middle
See if they're learning what

00:40:47.316 --> 00:40:47.976 A:middle
they need to learn.

00:40:47.976 --> 00:40:49.706 A:middle
And if we need to do more, we'll

00:40:49.706 --> 00:40:50.146 A:middle
do more.

00:40:50.686 --> 00:40:53.386 A:middle
It's impossible to rush the

00:40:53.386 --> 00:40:55.216 A:middle
creative process of making a

00:40:55.216 --> 00:40:57.496 A:middle
game because so much of what's

00:40:57.496 --> 00:40:58.846 A:middle
special about the games that you

00:40:58.846 --> 00:41:01.726 A:middle
remember are decisions that seem

00:40:58.846 --> 00:41:01.726 A:middle
remember are decisions that seem

00:41:01.866 --> 00:41:03.456 A:middle
very obvious and very small but

00:41:03.456 --> 00:41:05.616 A:middle
take a really, really long time

00:41:05.616 --> 00:41:06.786 A:middle
to arrive at.

00:41:06.786 --> 00:41:08.486 A:middle
And you can't hire more people

00:41:08.486 --> 00:41:09.406 A:middle
to get there faster.

00:41:09.406 --> 00:41:12.006 A:middle
You just have to sit with it and

00:41:12.006 --> 00:41:13.866 A:middle
continue working on it until the

00:41:13.866 --> 00:41:14.976 A:middle
best solutions arise.

00:41:17.276 --> 00:41:18.886 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So Sam said something here

00:41:18.886 --> 00:41:20.176 A:middle
that I want to expand on.

00:41:21.196 --> 00:41:22.856 A:middle
More people are not going to fix

00:41:22.906 --> 00:41:24.176 A:middle
a creative problem.

00:41:24.666 --> 00:41:26.906 A:middle
Great artists are patient.

00:41:27.456 --> 00:41:29.326 A:middle
Sometimes you just get writer's

00:41:29.436 --> 00:41:30.856 A:middle
block and there's no amount of

00:41:30.896 --> 00:41:32.296 A:middle
conversation that's going to fix

00:41:32.296 --> 00:41:34.856 A:middle
it, so you have to wait and just

00:41:34.856 --> 00:41:36.326 A:middle
let that creative process

00:41:36.326 --> 00:41:36.846 A:middle
happen.

00:41:37.356 --> 00:41:38.506 A:middle
And that's okay.

00:41:38.986 --> 00:41:41.206 A:middle
It's a part of the process, and

00:41:41.206 --> 00:41:42.866 A:middle
sometimes that's exactly what is

00:41:42.866 --> 00:41:44.586 A:middle
needed to produce quality.

00:41:44.876 --> 00:41:47.336 A:middle
So the theme really from these

00:41:47.416 --> 00:41:49.976 A:middle
last 3 clips is to go out and

00:41:50.136 --> 00:41:52.626 A:middle
try your designs in context with

00:41:52.626 --> 00:41:53.376 A:middle
real people.

00:41:54.086 --> 00:41:55.926 A:middle
Show people prototypes and learn

00:41:55.926 --> 00:41:56.556 A:middle
from their feedback.

00:41:57.376 --> 00:41:58.696 A:middle
This is a really essential

00:41:58.796 --> 00:42:00.646 A:middle
technique to help work through

00:41:58.796 --> 00:42:00.646 A:middle
technique to help work through

00:42:00.646 --> 00:42:01.866 A:middle
your design decisions.

00:42:01.866 --> 00:42:05.306 A:middle
So we can learn a lot from each

00:42:05.306 --> 00:42:07.356 A:middle
other, so I wanted to know what

00:42:07.356 --> 00:42:09.506 A:middle
advice would one designer give

00:42:09.666 --> 00:42:10.686 A:middle
to another designer.

00:42:11.336 --> 00:42:14.656 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Learn how to accept, and

00:42:14.776 --> 00:42:16.296 A:middle
sort, and prioritize the

00:42:16.296 --> 00:42:17.846 A:middle
feedback as it comes in, whether

00:42:17.846 --> 00:42:19.036 A:middle
it's from yourself or from

00:42:19.036 --> 00:42:19.336 A:middle
others.

00:42:19.906 --> 00:42:21.116 A:middle
You will learn so much more

00:42:21.116 --> 00:42:22.226 A:middle
quickly than if you are

00:42:22.226 --> 00:42:23.966 A:middle
defensive and you just, like,

00:42:23.966 --> 00:42:24.616 A:middle
buckle down.

00:42:26.496 --> 00:42:27.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I personally struggle with

00:42:27.706 --> 00:42:28.526 A:middle
this.

00:42:28.616 --> 00:42:30.266 A:middle
I can almost not help becoming

00:42:30.266 --> 00:42:32.326 A:middle
defensive when I hear feedback

00:42:32.356 --> 00:42:33.406 A:middle
on a project I'm working on.

00:42:33.406 --> 00:42:35.286 A:middle
It's like this instinctual

00:42:35.286 --> 00:42:37.326 A:middle
reaction, especially if I just

00:42:37.356 --> 00:42:38.956 A:middle
spent late nights and weekends

00:42:38.956 --> 00:42:40.026 A:middle
working on something.

00:42:41.066 --> 00:42:43.406 A:middle
But still, I know it's

00:42:43.406 --> 00:42:46.216 A:middle
important, but I wanted to know

00:42:46.216 --> 00:42:46.556 A:middle
why.

00:42:46.736 --> 00:42:49.596 A:middle
Again, why is it important to be

00:42:49.646 --> 00:42:50.676 A:middle
open to feedback?

00:42:52.646 --> 00:42:53.966 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I think there's also just a

00:42:53.966 --> 00:42:55.206 A:middle
reality, which is after you've

00:42:55.206 --> 00:42:57.126 A:middle
used your own work for some

00:42:57.126 --> 00:42:58.716 A:middle
amount of time, you naturally

00:42:58.716 --> 00:43:00.396 A:middle
develop some blind spots.

00:42:58.716 --> 00:43:00.396 A:middle
develop some blind spots.

00:43:00.396 --> 00:43:01.966 A:middle
And that's where having a really

00:43:01.966 --> 00:43:03.166 A:middle
great, collaborative team and

00:43:03.166 --> 00:43:04.916 A:middle
people that you trust around you

00:43:04.916 --> 00:43:06.986 A:middle
to help critique your work is a

00:43:07.026 --> 00:43:07.896 A:middle
really important part of the

00:43:07.896 --> 00:43:09.126 A:middle
design process.

00:43:09.336 --> 00:43:10.406 A:middle
So you can get fresh eyes on

00:43:10.406 --> 00:43:11.926 A:middle
stuff and trust that people have

00:43:12.166 --> 00:43:13.436 A:middle
the good intentions and they're

00:43:13.566 --> 00:43:14.986 A:middle
going to be able to give you

00:43:14.986 --> 00:43:16.006 A:middle
great insights of how you can

00:43:16.006 --> 00:43:16.406 A:middle
improve.

00:43:17.776 --> 00:43:18.276 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Totally.

00:43:18.956 --> 00:43:19.646 A:middle
I've been there.

00:43:19.646 --> 00:43:21.026 A:middle
I've definitely been too close

00:43:21.026 --> 00:43:22.396 A:middle
on a project and lost sight of a

00:43:22.396 --> 00:43:24.266 A:middle
big picture or overlooked some

00:43:24.456 --> 00:43:24.756 A:middle
detail.

00:43:25.236 --> 00:43:27.196 A:middle
So by being open to feedback,

00:43:28.156 --> 00:43:30.286 A:middle
it's really easy then to have

00:43:30.346 --> 00:43:32.596 A:middle
someone else like your team or

00:43:32.596 --> 00:43:33.306 A:middle
somebody that you asked a

00:43:33.306 --> 00:43:35.346 A:middle
question to give you something,

00:43:35.346 --> 00:43:36.506 A:middle
some piece of information that

00:43:36.506 --> 00:43:37.566 A:middle
can help you improve your

00:43:37.566 --> 00:43:38.076 A:middle
designs.

00:43:39.066 --> 00:43:40.546 A:middle
And I really like that May-Li

00:43:40.646 --> 00:43:42.336 A:middle
said this word, "trust," to

00:43:42.336 --> 00:43:43.746 A:middle
trust the people around you.

00:43:44.836 --> 00:43:46.646 A:middle
So be open to feedback.

00:43:47.396 --> 00:43:48.986 A:middle
It makes everything better and

00:43:48.986 --> 00:43:50.816 A:middle
just ups the overall quality of

00:43:50.846 --> 00:43:52.726 A:middle
design in your work.

00:43:53.276 --> 00:43:55.876 A:middle
So this next technique is more

00:43:55.876 --> 00:43:57.706 A:middle
of a mindset, and it came up

00:43:57.756 --> 00:43:59.396 A:middle
when I asked Cas, who works on

00:43:59.476 --> 00:44:01.626 A:middle
platform patterns, "How do you

00:43:59.476 --> 00:44:01.626 A:middle
platform patterns, "How do you

00:44:01.626 --> 00:44:03.506 A:middle
approach designing for so many

00:44:03.556 --> 00:44:03.866 A:middle
people?"

00:44:03.866 --> 00:44:06.876 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Knowing what you don't know,

00:44:08.296 --> 00:44:08.696 A:middle
in a way.

00:44:08.976 --> 00:44:12.286 A:middle
What I mean is that if you're

00:44:12.286 --> 00:44:13.266 A:middle
looking at these things or if

00:44:13.266 --> 00:44:14.346 A:middle
you're designing for these

00:44:14.346 --> 00:44:15.396 A:middle
things, obviously, you have

00:44:16.306 --> 00:44:19.046 A:middle
ideas and ways of using a

00:44:19.046 --> 00:44:20.516 A:middle
certain device or an app in your

00:44:20.516 --> 00:44:21.396 A:middle
own way, in your own

00:44:21.396 --> 00:44:22.826 A:middle
environment, in your own habits,

00:44:23.356 --> 00:44:24.856 A:middle
and you might know a little bit

00:44:24.856 --> 00:44:26.266 A:middle
about how your friends are using

00:44:26.336 --> 00:44:27.956 A:middle
it, or how you've seen other

00:44:27.956 --> 00:44:29.296 A:middle
people use it, or maybe feedback

00:44:29.296 --> 00:44:30.996 A:middle
you're getting, but it's a

00:44:30.996 --> 00:44:32.426 A:middle
really big world, and there's a

00:44:32.426 --> 00:44:34.516 A:middle
lot of people out there, and

00:44:34.946 --> 00:44:35.876 A:middle
they all have their own needs,

00:44:35.936 --> 00:44:38.076 A:middle
their own habits, their own way

00:44:38.076 --> 00:44:39.356 A:middle
of going through life.

00:44:39.356 --> 00:44:40.546 A:middle
And so you have to be very

00:44:40.546 --> 00:44:42.766 A:middle
mindful that how you think about

00:44:42.766 --> 00:44:43.926 A:middle
things or your opinions are not

00:44:43.926 --> 00:44:45.506 A:middle
always, first of all, correct

00:44:45.506 --> 00:44:48.896 A:middle
ones, nor the only ones.

00:44:49.696 --> 00:44:50.916 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I really like how Cas put

00:44:50.916 --> 00:44:53.146 A:middle
this at the beginning -- know

00:44:53.196 --> 00:44:54.146 A:middle
that you don't know.

00:44:54.986 --> 00:44:56.286 A:middle
And he also used this word

00:44:56.286 --> 00:44:57.326 A:middle
"modesty" through our

00:44:57.326 --> 00:44:58.176 A:middle
conversation.

00:44:58.686 --> 00:45:00.156 A:middle
To be unassuming when you're

00:44:58.686 --> 00:45:00.156 A:middle
To be unassuming when you're

00:45:00.156 --> 00:45:02.046 A:middle
designing for so many people.

00:45:03.016 --> 00:45:05.376 A:middle
And that is a really great

00:45:05.416 --> 00:45:06.646 A:middle
headspace to be in when you're

00:45:06.646 --> 00:45:08.846 A:middle
approaching design; to be modest

00:45:09.456 --> 00:45:10.686 A:middle
and to be mindful.

00:45:11.316 --> 00:45:14.656 A:middle
So how do you help keep people's

00:45:14.656 --> 00:45:16.606 A:middle
experiences top of mind when

00:45:16.606 --> 00:45:17.246 A:middle
you're designing?

00:45:17.906 --> 00:45:19.826 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So in many ways, I just have

00:45:19.826 --> 00:45:21.966 A:middle
to be skeptical and ask

00:45:21.966 --> 00:45:23.516 A:middle
questions if the idea in front

00:45:23.516 --> 00:45:25.566 A:middle
of me, is that going to work for

00:45:25.566 --> 00:45:27.266 A:middle
someone in a wheelchair, for

00:45:27.266 --> 00:45:27.726 A:middle
example?

00:45:27.726 --> 00:45:28.866 A:middle
Is that going to work for

00:45:28.866 --> 00:45:33.086 A:middle
someone that has never used this

00:45:33.086 --> 00:45:33.686 A:middle
app before?

00:45:33.686 --> 00:45:36.476 A:middle
Is it going to work for someone

00:45:36.476 --> 00:45:37.996 A:middle
coming from a PC to a Mac?

00:45:37.996 --> 00:45:39.716 A:middle
You just have to ask lots of

00:45:39.716 --> 00:45:41.756 A:middle
questions, and it can just start

00:45:41.756 --> 00:45:43.206 A:middle
people thinking about, oh, yeah,

00:45:43.206 --> 00:45:44.456 A:middle
did I care enough to consider

00:45:44.456 --> 00:45:47.346 A:middle
that aspect of it?

00:45:47.626 --> 00:45:49.816 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Right. So this may seem

00:45:49.816 --> 00:45:51.996 A:middle
really simple, but it's

00:45:51.996 --> 00:45:53.756 A:middle
important to ask questions,

00:45:54.106 --> 00:45:55.236 A:middle
especially from different

00:45:55.236 --> 00:45:55.956 A:middle
perspectives.

00:45:56.466 --> 00:45:57.296 A:middle
That's going to help you

00:45:57.296 --> 00:45:58.836 A:middle
maintain quality throughout your

00:45:58.836 --> 00:46:00.366 A:middle
work and keep those other

00:45:58.836 --> 00:46:00.366 A:middle
work and keep those other

00:46:00.366 --> 00:46:02.706 A:middle
people's experiences in mind.

00:46:03.636 --> 00:46:05.296 A:middle
So design is a really

00:46:05.296 --> 00:46:06.936 A:middle
collaborative process, and

00:46:06.936 --> 00:46:08.336 A:middle
there's a lot that goes into

00:46:08.336 --> 00:46:09.706 A:middle
making collaboration work.

00:46:10.396 --> 00:46:12.146 A:middle
At one point or another, we're

00:46:12.146 --> 00:46:13.386 A:middle
all going to start on a new

00:46:13.386 --> 00:46:15.636 A:middle
project or a new team, so what

00:46:15.686 --> 00:46:17.806 A:middle
helps make that process a little

00:46:17.806 --> 00:46:18.456 A:middle
bit easier?

00:46:20.306 --> 00:46:21.006 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I always like to set

00:46:21.306 --> 00:46:22.236 A:middle
expectations upfront.

00:46:22.886 --> 00:46:24.666 A:middle
I just say, hey, this is how I

00:46:24.736 --> 00:46:25.016 A:middle
am.

00:46:25.576 --> 00:46:27.956 A:middle
This is how I work.

00:46:28.006 --> 00:46:29.386 A:middle
This is how I communicate.

00:46:29.386 --> 00:46:30.196 A:middle
How do you work?

00:46:30.196 --> 00:46:31.356 A:middle
How do you communicate?

00:46:31.356 --> 00:46:32.806 A:middle
What's your preferred method of

00:46:32.866 --> 00:46:33.586 A:middle
communication?

00:46:33.586 --> 00:46:36.076 A:middle
And by the way, here's the goals

00:46:36.146 --> 00:46:38.126 A:middle
that I think we are working

00:46:38.126 --> 00:46:38.516 A:middle
toward.

00:46:38.866 --> 00:46:39.856 A:middle
And here are the things that are

00:46:39.856 --> 00:46:40.566 A:middle
important to me.

00:46:40.566 --> 00:46:42.246 A:middle
And please share with me the

00:46:42.246 --> 00:46:43.186 A:middle
same for you.

00:46:43.746 --> 00:46:45.396 A:middle
And I'll always sort of say it

00:46:45.396 --> 00:46:46.666 A:middle
with a caveat like, "We're going

00:46:46.666 --> 00:46:47.946 A:middle
to get all this business out of

00:46:47.946 --> 00:46:48.836 A:middle
the way, and we're going to

00:46:48.946 --> 00:46:52.826 A:middle
speak very directly about it."

00:46:53.086 --> 00:46:55.666 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I know for me, talking about

00:46:55.666 --> 00:46:56.896 A:middle
communication can be awkward,

00:46:57.666 --> 00:46:59.056 A:middle
but after I tried this

00:46:59.186 --> 00:47:00.686 A:middle
technique, I learned that it

00:46:59.186 --> 00:47:00.686 A:middle
technique, I learned that it

00:47:00.686 --> 00:47:03.316 A:middle
helps avoid so much drama and

00:47:03.316 --> 00:47:04.016 A:middle
confusion.

00:47:04.446 --> 00:47:06.866 A:middle
So talk about communication,

00:47:07.566 --> 00:47:08.506 A:middle
especially if you're working on

00:47:08.616 --> 00:47:08.986 A:middle
teams.

00:47:09.626 --> 00:47:11.346 A:middle
Work towards the same goal about

00:47:11.346 --> 00:47:12.556 A:middle
creating something great.

00:47:14.026 --> 00:47:16.396 A:middle
So really, these six techniques

00:47:16.796 --> 00:47:18.596 A:middle
are all about caring about the

00:47:18.596 --> 00:47:20.596 A:middle
other people and having tools to

00:47:20.676 --> 00:47:22.566 A:middle
talk about it, and you have to

00:47:22.716 --> 00:47:24.056 A:middle
care about other people and put

00:47:24.056 --> 00:47:24.956 A:middle
yourself second.

00:47:25.766 --> 00:47:27.506 A:middle
Be mindful of their lives and be

00:47:27.506 --> 00:47:29.816 A:middle
modest about your own because we

00:47:29.816 --> 00:47:31.606 A:middle
just learned you can't assume.

00:47:31.876 --> 00:47:33.216 A:middle
You have to go out and try your

00:47:33.216 --> 00:47:35.166 A:middle
designs through prototyping and

00:47:35.166 --> 00:47:36.826 A:middle
also really remain open to

00:47:36.926 --> 00:47:37.476 A:middle
feedback.

00:47:37.976 --> 00:47:39.256 A:middle
That's essential to making

00:47:39.256 --> 00:47:42.586 A:middle
progress in design because, as

00:47:42.586 --> 00:47:44.876 A:middle
May-Li said, we all develop

00:47:44.956 --> 00:47:47.866 A:middle
blind spots, and we're not only

00:47:47.866 --> 00:47:50.026 A:middle
designing to make progress, but

00:47:50.026 --> 00:47:51.356 A:middle
we want to get closer to

00:47:51.356 --> 00:47:52.886 A:middle
reaching our own aspirations and

00:47:52.886 --> 00:47:53.446 A:middle
our own goals.

00:47:54.146 --> 00:47:56.866 A:middle
So these techniques are used by

00:47:57.016 --> 00:47:58.656 A:middle
real designers that I talked to,

00:47:59.126 --> 00:48:00.876 A:middle
and they help them go through

00:47:59.126 --> 00:48:00.876 A:middle
and they help them go through

00:48:00.876 --> 00:48:02.176 A:middle
the process of designing, and it

00:48:02.176 --> 00:48:03.566 A:middle
makes their days a little bit

00:48:03.566 --> 00:48:05.836 A:middle
easier, so I hope they can help

00:48:06.096 --> 00:48:06.936 A:middle
you too.

00:48:07.856 --> 00:48:09.806 A:middle
So after all of these

00:48:09.806 --> 00:48:11.956 A:middle
interviews, I learned that

00:48:12.156 --> 00:48:14.636 A:middle
quality is the result of time,

00:48:15.056 --> 00:48:16.326 A:middle
effort, and care.

00:48:17.116 --> 00:48:19.316 A:middle
It's considered, it's crafted,

00:48:19.686 --> 00:48:21.096 A:middle
and it means something different

00:48:21.096 --> 00:48:21.906 A:middle
to different people.

00:48:23.416 --> 00:48:24.976 A:middle
I also learned that quality

00:48:24.976 --> 00:48:27.366 A:middle
impacts our every day, that your

00:48:27.366 --> 00:48:29.076 A:middle
intentions are truly felt.

00:48:29.956 --> 00:48:32.316 A:middle
High quality evokes trust, and

00:48:32.316 --> 00:48:34.246 A:middle
that's really important, as well

00:48:34.246 --> 00:48:36.786 A:middle
as it has to be earned.

00:48:36.936 --> 00:48:38.416 A:middle
It's also important to strive

00:48:38.416 --> 00:48:41.166 A:middle
for simplicity, to aspire to be

00:48:41.296 --> 00:48:43.126 A:middle
stunning, and design to be

00:48:43.246 --> 00:48:43.536 A:middle
timeless.

00:48:44.446 --> 00:48:45.966 A:middle
Just think about how your app or

00:48:45.966 --> 00:48:47.726 A:middle
game can have a positive impact

00:48:47.926 --> 00:48:49.386 A:middle
on people's lives.

00:48:49.936 --> 00:48:51.856 A:middle
And finally, working towards

00:48:51.856 --> 00:48:53.116 A:middle
quality is all about

00:48:53.216 --> 00:48:54.986 A:middle
communication, collaboration,

00:48:55.076 --> 00:48:57.496 A:middle
and understanding, especially

00:48:57.496 --> 00:48:58.866 A:middle
understanding the people you are

00:48:58.866 --> 00:48:59.626 A:middle
designing for.

00:49:00.906 --> 00:49:02.586 A:middle
So really, quality is a

00:49:02.676 --> 00:49:03.166 A:middle
principle.

00:49:03.166 --> 00:49:06.156 A:middle
It is intentional, and it's

00:49:06.156 --> 00:49:07.326 A:middle
something that you have to ask

00:49:07.326 --> 00:49:09.326 A:middle
yourself, what does quality mean

00:49:09.326 --> 00:49:09.916 A:middle
to you?

00:49:10.316 --> 00:49:11.506 A:middle
And you need to know your

00:49:11.506 --> 00:49:14.196 A:middle
interpretation to go forward, to

00:49:14.196 --> 00:49:16.486 A:middle
put in that hard work that meets

00:49:16.486 --> 00:49:18.076 A:middle
your expectations and hits your

00:49:18.076 --> 00:49:21.006 A:middle
aspirations because, at the end

00:49:21.006 --> 00:49:23.046 A:middle
of the day, you're not designing

00:49:23.046 --> 00:49:23.656 A:middle
for you.

00:49:24.096 --> 00:49:25.676 A:middle
You're designing for other

00:49:25.676 --> 00:49:27.226 A:middle
people who are going to use your

00:49:27.566 --> 00:49:28.466 A:middle
app or your game.

00:49:29.066 --> 00:49:30.846 A:middle
So make great designs for them.

00:49:32.606 --> 00:49:34.176 A:middle
Now, there are two important

00:49:34.176 --> 00:49:35.726 A:middle
statements on quality in great

00:49:35.726 --> 00:49:37.856 A:middle
design that stand alone.

00:49:38.616 --> 00:49:39.646 A:middle
These are going to play back to

00:49:39.646 --> 00:49:41.536 A:middle
back, and I hope each offers

00:49:41.536 --> 00:49:42.596 A:middle
something different that you can

00:49:42.596 --> 00:49:44.396 A:middle
take away from today.

00:49:45.396 --> 00:49:49.216 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Sensing the human behind the

00:49:49.216 --> 00:49:51.626 A:middle
experience I think is really an

00:49:52.036 --> 00:49:53.696 A:middle
earmark of something great.

00:49:58.036 --> 00:50:01.096 A:middle
&gt;&gt; A great design is going to be

00:49:58.036 --> 00:50:01.096 A:middle
&gt;&gt; A great design is going to be

00:50:01.096 --> 00:50:02.586 A:middle
the product of tremendous amount

00:50:02.586 --> 00:50:04.666 A:middle
of effort, and creativity, and

00:50:04.856 --> 00:50:07.316 A:middle
skill, and [laughs] late nights.

00:50:07.476 --> 00:50:10.086 A:middle
It's going to seem effortless,

00:50:10.186 --> 00:50:12.606 A:middle
and it should hopefully recede

00:50:12.606 --> 00:50:14.146 A:middle
in people's consciousness.

00:50:14.736 --> 00:50:16.906 A:middle
And in a way, I think you're

00:50:16.906 --> 00:50:18.656 A:middle
very aware of an interface which

00:50:18.656 --> 00:50:20.456 A:middle
has been poorly designed, and

00:50:20.456 --> 00:50:21.706 A:middle
you're not at all aware of an

00:50:21.706 --> 00:50:23.356 A:middle
interface which has been well

00:50:23.356 --> 00:50:23.826 A:middle
designed.

00:50:28.296 --> 00:50:29.546 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So I talked to a lot of

00:50:29.546 --> 00:50:31.586 A:middle
people, and I saved something

00:50:31.626 --> 00:50:33.446 A:middle
special just for the end.

00:50:34.266 --> 00:50:35.856 A:middle
Since I had the opportunity to

00:50:35.936 --> 00:50:37.026 A:middle
talk to so many different

00:50:37.026 --> 00:50:39.566 A:middle
designers, I had to ask them onw

00:50:39.936 --> 00:50:40.906 A:middle
final question, and it's

00:50:40.906 --> 00:50:42.226 A:middle
something that I've always

00:50:42.226 --> 00:50:45.036 A:middle
wanted, wondered myself: What

00:50:45.676 --> 00:50:47.536 A:middle
are designers' favorite colors?

00:50:50.896 --> 00:50:51.906 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Oh, wow.

00:50:52.316 --> 00:50:53.916 A:middle
&gt;&gt; My favorite color?

00:50:53.916 --> 00:50:55.716 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I have to say--

00:50:55.916 --> 00:50:57.066 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Is there such a thing?

00:50:57.066 --> 00:50:58.816 A:middle
I don't think so.

00:50:58.896 --> 00:51:00.076 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I would have said glitter,

00:50:58.896 --> 00:51:00.076 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I would have said glitter,

00:51:00.076 --> 00:51:01.076 A:middle
but it's not a color.

00:51:01.446 --> 00:51:02.436 A:middle
&gt;&gt; One of the things that I

00:51:02.436 --> 00:51:04.496 A:middle
really love is Tahitian blue.

00:51:04.616 --> 00:51:06.736 A:middle
&gt;&gt; But colors to me are like

00:51:06.736 --> 00:51:09.006 A:middle
moods, and I do not have the

00:51:09.006 --> 00:51:09.936 A:middle
same mood every day.

00:51:09.936 --> 00:51:10.796 A:middle
I don't think I even have the

00:51:10.796 --> 00:51:12.516 A:middle
same mood every hour, so.

00:51:12.516 --> 00:51:13.436 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I really like white.

00:51:14.236 --> 00:51:15.186 A:middle
Is it really a color?

00:51:15.376 --> 00:51:16.366 A:middle
I think that's one of the

00:51:16.366 --> 00:51:17.486 A:middle
reasons why I like it.

00:51:17.486 --> 00:51:18.646 A:middle
&gt;&gt; My favorite color has been

00:51:18.646 --> 00:51:19.046 A:middle
amber.

00:51:19.556 --> 00:51:20.896 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I mean, lately, it's been

00:51:20.896 --> 00:51:22.216 A:middle
green for some reason.

00:51:22.216 --> 00:51:22.926 A:middle
I don't know why.

00:51:23.026 --> 00:51:25.746 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I got to go back on this

00:51:25.746 --> 00:51:26.046 A:middle
answer.

00:51:26.046 --> 00:51:29.346 A:middle
Oh, it's actually Pantone 347.

00:51:29.346 --> 00:51:30.856 A:middle
&gt;&gt; My favorite color is blue.

00:51:31.376 --> 00:51:33.996 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Like a happy blue, and blue

00:51:33.996 --> 00:51:35.566 A:middle
is, like, always such a color of

00:51:35.566 --> 00:51:37.076 A:middle
responsibility, which is, like,

00:51:37.426 --> 00:51:37.976 A:middle
so me.

00:51:38.046 --> 00:51:39.806 A:middle
&gt;&gt; But I just think it's, like,

00:51:39.806 --> 00:51:41.596 A:middle
soft and friendly.

00:51:42.036 --> 00:51:44.886 A:middle
And food that's pink tastes

00:51:44.886 --> 00:51:44.976 A:middle
good.

00:51:45.066 --> 00:51:46.416 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I'm going to go with red.

00:51:46.416 --> 00:51:47.506 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Throw out a hex value.

00:51:47.506 --> 00:51:48.996 A:middle
I don't have a favorite color.

00:51:49.446 --> 00:51:50.466 A:middle
Every color's great.

00:51:50.466 --> 00:51:53.316 A:middle
&gt;&gt; [laughs] All right, maybe

00:51:53.316 --> 00:51:54.886 A:middle
I'll just answer for this moment

00:51:55.096 --> 00:51:56.326 A:middle
in time.

00:51:56.326 --> 00:51:58.426 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I don't wear any green.

00:51:58.596 --> 00:52:00.376 A:middle
My car's not green.

00:51:58.596 --> 00:52:00.376 A:middle
My car's not green.

00:52:00.486 --> 00:52:04.866 A:middle
But I just like the idea of

00:52:04.926 --> 00:52:05.346 A:middle
green.

00:52:05.696 --> 00:52:07.746 A:middle
&gt;&gt; And I can't pick one because

00:52:08.026 --> 00:52:09.326 A:middle
I wouldn't be able to pick a

00:52:09.326 --> 00:52:12.966 A:middle
single musical note, so I'll use

00:52:12.966 --> 00:52:14.476 A:middle
all of them where it makes

00:52:14.476 --> 00:52:14.876 A:middle
sense.

00:52:15.786 --> 00:52:17.846 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I'll need to check the spec

00:52:17.846 --> 00:52:19.046 A:middle
on that, I think.

00:52:19.456 --> 00:52:20.806 A:middle
System blue, of course.

00:52:20.806 --> 00:52:20.936 A:middle
Yeah.

00:52:26.126 --> 00:52:27.466 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Special thanks to everyone

00:52:27.466 --> 00:52:28.486 A:middle
who participated in these

00:52:28.486 --> 00:52:29.026 A:middle
interviews.

00:52:29.476 --> 00:52:30.766 A:middle
Thank you all so much.

00:52:30.826 --> 00:52:32.276 A:middle
Have a great WWDC.
